\subsubsection{\QCD\ multijet background}
\label{sec:bkg_QCD}

Typically, MC event simulation cannot properly reproduce the shape and normalization of the
\QCD\ multijet background, in particular, in the phase space of the analysis with an isolated and high-\pt lepton on top of four jets. 
Significantly high event count samples would also be required, and without any guarantee that the result
could be safely used as a description of this type of background, a data-based technique is applied.

A control region is selected in the $\mu$+jets final state by inverting the
isolation requirement for muons, i.e., $I_{\textrm{rel}}^{\mu}>0.2$, leaving all other identification requirements unchanged. 
The inverted cut value of 0.2 reflects a tradeoff between the event count and the contamination expected in the control region from non-\QCD\ processes, i.e., signal and \PW+jets events. 
In the $\mathrm{e}$+jets final state the electron candidate is required to fail a looser set of identification criteria, the so-called ``veto'' identification (Table~\ref{seltagandprobeeff}). 
A better estimate of the \QCD\ multijet background is found in the \texttt{ECAL} endcaps~\citeTH{topobs_CMS_jhep} where the fraction of nongenuine electrons is higher than the barrel. 
In both $\mu$+jets and $\mathrm{e}$+jets final states, the control regions contain no \cPqb-tagged jets to reduce the contamination from other non-\QCD\ processes, and hence are expected 
to be enriched mostly in \QCD\ multijet events.

Figure~\ref{fig:qcdparam} shows the distributions of the three mass variables, reconstructed in the \QCD\ multijet control regions. 
It is seen that the event count in the $\mathrm{e}$+jets is significantly higher than in $\mu$+jets final state, owing to the dominant contribution from nongenuine electrons.
Following the approach of~\citeTH{topobs_CMS_jhep} the shape of the \QCD\ multijet background is assumed to be the same in the control and signal regions. 
The shape is modeled with a nonparametric kernel approach~\cite{Cranmer:2000du}. 
A fair agreement is observed for all mass variables and categories.

\begin{figure}[!ht]
\centering
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/mjj_mu_QCD}}
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/mthad_mu_QCD}}
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/mtlep_mu_QCD}}
\\
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/mjj_e_QCD}}
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/mthad_e_QCD}}
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/mtlep_e_QCD}}
\caption[Parametrized \QCD\ multijet distributions for the dijet invariant mass, and hadronic and leptonic top mass in the $\ell$+jets final state using pPb collisions at $\rootsNN=8.16$\,\TeV]{
Parametrized \QCD\ multijet distributions as a function of \mjj (a), $m_{\cPqt_{\textrm{had}}}$ (b) and $m_{\cPqt_{\textrm{lep}}}$ (c) using events with no \cPqb-tagged jets in 
(a--c) $\mu$+jets---failing $I_{\textrm{rel}}^{\mu}>0.2$ requirement---and (d--f) $\mathrm{e}$+jets---failing the veto identification---final states, respectively~\citeAN{AN-17-043}.
}
\label{fig:qcdparam}
\end{figure}

The initial normalization of the \QCD\ multijet background is estimated from events with low $\ptmiss<20$\,\GeV. 
A fit is performed using the distributions of \QCD\ multijet, and \ttbar\ and \PW+jets processes derived from the control regions and MC simulation, respectively.  
The contributions from \ttbar\ and \PW+jets are left to float within 30\% of their initial estimates based on their theory cross sections. 
A 50-100\% systematic uncertainty is assigned to the result of the fit that is displayed in Fig.~\ref{fig:qcdmetmetfits} separately for the $\mu$+jets and $\mathrm{e}$+jets final states. 
Although slight mismodeling is observed, the outcome of the fit serves the purpose of the data-based technique, i.e., to find an initial estimate for the number of \QCD\ multijet 
events fulfilling the analysis selection.  
Table~\ref{tab:qcdnorm} summarizes the number of \QCD\ multijet events estimated in each event category and the associated uncertainty which is used as a constraint 
when extracting the \ttbar\ cross section, as described in the following.

\begin{figure}[!ht]
\centering
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/metfit_mu1l4j2q}}
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/metfit_mu1l4j1b1q}}
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/metfit_mu1l4j2b}}
\\
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/metfit_e1l4j2q}}
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/metfit_e1l4j1b1q}}
\subfloat[][]{\includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figures/pPb8TeV/metfit_e1l4j2b}}

\caption[Initial estimation of the \QCD\ multijet background based on \ptmiss distributions in the $\ell$+jets final state using pPb collisions at $\rootsNN=8.16$\,\TeV]{
Fits to the \ptmiss distribution in the $\mu$+jets (a--c) and $\mathrm{e}$+jets (d--f) final states in the 1$\ell$4j0b (a,\,d), 1$\ell$4j1b (b,\,e), and 1$\ell$4j2b (c,\,f) event categories.
The \QCD\ normalization estimated from the fit is shown in the captions, along with its statistical uncertainty~\citeAN{AN-17-043}.
}
\label{fig:qcdmetmetfits}
\end{figure}


